<li id="cite_note-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="news" id="CITEREFRanderson2008">Randerson, James (13 May 2008). <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2008/may/12/peopleinscience.religion/print" class="external text" title="http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2008/may/12/peopleinscience.religion/print" rel="nofollow">"Childish superstition: Einstein's letter makes view of religion relatively clear"</a>. The Guardian<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2008/may/12/peopleinscience.religion/print" class="external free" title="http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2008/may/12/peopleinscience.religion/print" rel="nofollow">http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2008/may/12/peopleinscience.religion/print</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-05-14</span>.  "In the letter, he states: "The word god is for me nothing more than the expression and product of human weaknesses, the Bible a collection of honourable, but still primitive legends which are nevertheless pretty childish. No interpretation no matter how subtle can (for me) change this.""</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Childish+superstition%3A+Einstein%27s+letter+makes+view+of+religion+relatively+clear&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Randerson&amp;rft.aufirst=James&amp;rft.au=Randerson%2C+James&amp;rft.date=13+May+2008&amp;rft.pub=The+Guardian&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.guardian.co.uk%2Fscience%2F2008%2Fmay%2F12%2Fpeopleinscience.religion%2Fprint&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:The_God_Delusion"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
